  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on financial reporting and record-keeping\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- FATF establishment (1989)\n- Proceeds of Crime Act (2002, UK)\n- Patriot Act (2001, US)\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- Broader regulatory requirements\n\n3. Modern Legislative Characteristics\n- Comprehensive customer due diligence\n- Enhanced transaction monitoring\n- Stricter reporting requirements\n- Substantial financial penalties\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n\n4. Technological Adaptation\n- Machine learning detection systems\n- Advanced risk assessment algorithms\n- Real-time transaction monitoring\n- Digital identity verification\n\n5. Current Trends\n- Increased regulatory complexity\n- Global standardization efforts\n- Emphasis on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Growing focus on cryptocurrency exchanges\n- Stronger enforcement mechanisms\n\nThese legislative developments reflect an increasingly sophisticated approach to preventing financial crimes, incorporating technological innovations and international collaboration.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of money laundering legislation?",
